<subSubSection id="2A09E91A21C45F64743585648D51C766" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D5271913BCC8F6607587E739BFF027EC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0793E12CE3270A2BEB17F1BB865A9F78" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="C22F80688C332E45A0C9A32522A87A3C" authorityName="Jordaens, Goergen &amp; De Meyer" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Mesembrius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesembrius copelandi" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copelandi">
<emphasis id="EAD4FDDFCBF759A58D534329658C1B0B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Mesembrius copelandi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. lack an apical pile brush on the profemur and have an unmodified metatibia. The ventral 1/4 of the profemur is black pilose with some longer yellow pile antero- and posteroventrally. The metaleg has long, yellow pile which becomes darker on the tarsi; the pile is much shorter on the posterior side. The metafemur has a patch of conspicuous black pile on the proximal 1/5 ventrally. The metabasitarsus is very long and almost as long as the metatibia; in all other species, the metabasitarsus is much shorter than the metatibia. The female is unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
